		<hr size="1">I am sure many of you look at the Big Guilds and think it would be cool to run one. Many of you probably think its just going arund and recruiting people and organizing raids. All I have to say to that is wrong wrong wrong.</P><P>I would have to compare being a Guild Leader to being the Head Camp Counselor at a day camp. Especially if you have 50+ members.  Now the key thing to remember is while the guild itself you will always have members that have their own selfish agenda. But those motives don't normally come out till the guild is raiding some zone to help out a class. Then low and behold members get mad at the selfish mofo. The mofo himself says something in guildchat to make the situation worse. Boom /guildremove idiot a few quick harsh words from the guildleader to the idiot and life goes back to normal<img src='http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tongue.gif' width=15 height=15 align=middle> not<img src='http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tongue.gif' width=15 height=15 align=middle></P><P>Typically the member that was kicked tries to see if he can get more to leave with him as his final revenge. </P><P>Between keeping order on loot. Which to this day I still haven't seen a loot policy that keeps everyone happy and making sure everyone else is happy. Running a guild can make EQ into a job more then a game. </P><P>Ultimately the guildleaders reward is seeing his guild accomplish its goals. Loot is usually the last thing the guildleader himself see's since he wants his members to be happy and will typically consider himself last.</P><P>I have been leader of many online teams. But I will have to say EQ guildleading is probably the most unique. You are strategist, Organizer, Counselor and yes even Babysitter. What prompted me to write this thread was all the guys I have ran into thinking that the guildleader has it so easy and gets all the good shit.</P><P><BR>Janus Slawslayer</P><P><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
