		<hr size="1">I think there are ups and downs to being a guild leader.  You are responsible for all organization and getting the webpage up, or delegating tasks etc.  But as guild leader of Elven Blades of Fury I find it to be fun.  I have been in a few guilds in which I didnt like.  Now that I have my own guild I can change in my guild what i couldnt change as a normal member of the other guilds.  Though I have yet to lead a raid(we are fairly new)  I enjoy my guild and have imposed a quest policy for all potential members and required that a potential must either have a reference from an officer or 2 references from normal members.  Either way the potential after the references must still be sent on a quest to prove that he actually wants into the guild.  Also we do not give out references to potentials that just ask, Can I get in yoru guild?, we must hunt with them or know them for a while.  Sure this may be a little too much but it helps make sure I dont get people that are gonna quit right away.  And so far it has worked excellently,  We are currently strong with aobut 25 members.</P><P><marquee scrollamount=2 height=30 direction=up width=50%><i><font color="#00BFFF">Kakullen - Lvl 14 Wood Elf Druid</marquee><BR><marquee direction=right width=50%><i><font color="#00ff00">Azareln - Lvl 19 Iksar Necro</marquee><BR><marquee height=30 direction=down scrollamount=2 width=50%><i><font color=yellow>Camlaan - Lvl 10 Iksar monk</marquee><BR><marquee direction=left width=50%><i><font color="00BFFF">Azarlen - Lvl 22 Wood Elf Warrior</marquee><BR><marquee direction=right width=50%><i><font color="blue">Elven Blades of Fury Rules</marquee><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
